The data powerfully illustrates these relationships. The opposition between Enmity and Compersion is starkly visible when comparing language that casts a political figure as guilty of an "appalling abuse of public trust" [1] with language that explicitly "commands my respect for his ability and perseverance" [2]. The first creates a climate of hostility, the second one of celebration; they are mutually exclusive.

Similarly, the fusion of Hope and Amity is a recurring rhetorical strategy. Calls to "stand together" (Amity) are directly linked to the goal of creating "the kind of nation that we deserve" (Hope) [3]. This pattern appears in different contexts, where appeals to "come together" (Amity) are framed as the path to "leave our children and grandchildren a stronger, better country" (Hope) [4]. The moderate link between Fear and Envy is also narratively clear, as threats like the destruction of social programs are tied directly to the resentful claim that it is being done to "make themselves even richer" [5].

### 5.2. Factorial Analysis: The Primacy of Envy

A series of two-way ANOVA tests were performed to assess the impact of Ideology and Era on each ECF dimension. Of the six core dimensions and two derived metrics, only **Envy** showed a statistically significant difference among the groups.

#### ANOVA Results Summary (p-values)
| Dimension | p-value | Significant (p < 0.05) |
|:---|:---:|:---:|
| ðŸ˜’ **Envy** | **0.027** | â­ **Yes** |
| ðŸ˜  Enmity | 0.078 | âŒ No |
| ðŸ˜¨ Fear | 0.662 | âŒ No |
| âœ¨ Hope | 0.528 | âŒ No |
| ðŸ¤ Amity | 0.822 | âŒ No |
| ðŸ˜Š Compersion | 0.496 | âŒ No |
| âš–ï¸ Polarity | 0.362 | âŒ No |
| ðŸ”¥ Intensity | 0.219 | âŒ No |

The significance of Envy (`p=0.027`) is driven by a dramatic divergence in scores between groups.

